 other (much more common) reasons, notably age, family responsibilities or physical unfitness. In particular, Civvies questions whether, if serviceman were the apex of manliness, were middle-class civilian men inevitably condemned to second-class, ‘unmanly’ status?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilians in warzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aMenzGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aEnglish home front.  aFirst World War.  acivilians.  acombatant sons.  amiddle-class men.  amiddle-class relationships.  apaterfamilias.  aprofit-making.  aservicemen.  avolunteer activities.  awartime consumers.  awhite-collar work.1 aUgolini, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611075640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526110756423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526110756/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles